\f6\fs45 \cf2 \cb3 Habit 1: Lead with Deliverable Specification
\f0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 The Practice:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Start every prompt with format, audience, and length constraints before describing the task.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Example:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  "Deliver a 7-slide outline for engineering VPs, \uc0\u8804 140 words per slide, technical depth appropriate for architecture decisions."\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Why It Works:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  GPT-5's bias toward thoroughness can produce 2,000-word analyses when you want 200-word summaries. Specifying deliverable characteristics up front prevents scope creep and over-teaching.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Common Failure:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Asking "help me with our API strategy" without specifying whether you want a comprehensive plan, a quick overview, or a specific recommendation. The model defaults to comprehensive.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa450\partightenfactor0

\f6\b\fs45 \cf2 \cb3 Habit 2: Pre-Bind Assumptions and Non-Goals
\f0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 The Practice:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Explicitly state what the model should assume and what areas to exclude.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Example:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  "Assumptions: B2B SaaS, Series A company, North American market, technical team. Non-goals: consumer products, international expansion, regulatory compliance."\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Why It Works:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  With only one clarifying question allowed, unstated assumptions become locked-in decisions. Pre-binding prevents the model from speculating in wrong directions.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Advanced Technique:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Include probability weightings: "Assume 70% likelihood of economic downturn; 30% growth scenario. Recommend strategies robust to both."\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa450\partightenfactor0

\f6\b\fs45 \cf2 \cb3 Habit 3: Declare Tool Policy and Budgets
\f0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 The Practice:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Specify which tools are allowed/forbidden and set usage limits.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Example:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  "Tool policy: Browse ON (max 2 sources, recent academic papers preferred), Python OFF, Canvas ON (id=market_analysis_v1). If browsing fails, proceed with training knowledge and flag limitations."\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Why It Works:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Prevents tool surprises and ensures reproducible workflows. Also allows you to control costs and latency based on task urgency.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Pro Tip:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Create standardized tool policy snippets for different use cases: research-heavy, code-focused, document creation, quick analysis.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa450\partightenfactor0

\f6\b\fs45 \cf2 \cb3 Habit 4: Choose Speed vs. Depth Explicitly
\f0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \cb3 The Practice:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Signal whether you want fast/minimal reasoning or slow/comprehensive analysis.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Example:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  "Quick assessment with 80% confidence threshold. Escalate to deep analysis only if confidence drops below 70%."\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Why It Works:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Matches cognitive load to task importance. Urgent decisions get fast responses; strategic decisions get thorough analysis.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cf2 \cb3 Implementation:
\f1\b0 \cf2 \cb3  Use consistent speed signals: "Fast/brief" for routine tasks, "Slow/deep" for high-stakes decisions.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa450\partightenfactor0

\f6\b\fs45 \cf2 \cb3 Habit 5: Define Acceptance Criteria
